  "text": "Memory pressure eviction in Kubernetes is implemented in the kubelet's eviction manager. The mechanism has two main components:\n\n1. **Memory Pressure Thresholds Definition:**\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_linux.go` defines default eviction thresholds with `DefaultEvictionHard` map containing \"memory.available\": \"100Mi\" for Linux systems\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/defaults_others.go` and `defaults_windows.go` provide platform-specific defaults\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/api/types.go` defines the eviction signal types, including `SignalMemoryAvailable` (memory.available) and `SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable` (allocatableMemory.available)\n   - The `Threshold` struct (in api/types.go) encapsulates threshold values, operators, grace periods, and minimum reclaim amounts\n\n2. **Eviction Manager Decision Logic:**\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/eviction_manager.go` contains the `managerImpl` type which implements the eviction manager\n   - The `synchronize()` function is the main control loop that:\n     a. Calls `makeSignalObservations()` to gather current memory availability metrics\n     b. Calls `thresholdsMet()` to compare observations against configured thresholds\n     c. Calls `nodeConditions()` to map memory signals (SignalMemoryAvailable, SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable) to NodeMemoryPressure conditions\n     d. Applies grace periods and evaluates if eviction should occur\n     e. When memory thresholds are met, calls `rankMemoryPressure()` to rank pods by their memory usage relative to requests\n     f. Evicts the highest-ranked pod via `evictPod()` to reclaim memory\n\n3. **Memory Observation and Ranking:**\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers.go` contains critical helper functions:\n     - `makeSignalObservations()` invokes platform-specific `makeMemoryAvailableSignalObservation()` to extract available and working-set memory from the summary stats\n     - `thresholdsMet()` compares available memory against configured thresholds using the OpLessThan operator\n     - `rankMemoryPressure()` orders pods by: (1) whether memory usage exceeds requests via `exceedMemoryRequests()`, (2) priority, then (3) absolute memory consumption\n     - `buildSignalToRankFunc()` maps memory signals to the `rankMemoryPressure()` function\n   - The signal-to-node-condition mapping (initialized in helpers.go) associates both SignalMemoryAvailable and SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable with v1.NodeMemoryPressure\n\n4. **Platform-Specific Details:**\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers_others.go` (non-Windows): extracts available memory as `summary.Node.Memory.AvailableBytes`\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/helpers_windows.go` (Windows): uses the system container `WindowsGlobalCommitMemory` to derive available memory\n\n5. **Configuration:**\n   - `pkg/kubelet/eviction/types.go` defines the `Config` struct which holds the eviction thresholds, grace periods, and other configuration needed by the manager"
